1.title: Daft Punk - Discovery on Talkin' Wax
1.plot: YouTube singer/songwriter Trevor Douglas stops by the Vinyl Pad to chat with The Geek about Daft Punk's seminal 2001 album Discovery.

1.title: The Mighty Accordion Band
1.plot: The Vinyl Geek takes a listen at The Mighty Accordion Band and gives his review of the album.

2.title: Do You Believe in Magic
2.plot: The Vinyl Geek reviews a record by one of his favorite bands and takes a trip down memory lane.

3.title: Harmonica Bands
3.plot: The Vinyl Geek discovers not one but two all harmonica based bands. Check out the short film mentioned in the show .

4.title: Stereo Dynamics!
4.plot: The vinyl geek tries to scare the hell out of his neighbors.

5.title: Buck Rogers
5.plot: The Vinyl Geek takes a trippy look into the 70's version of the future with the soundtrack to Buck Rogers.

6.title: Korla Pandit
6.plot: The Vinyl Geek travels to far away lands with Korla Pandit as his guide. Dig the crazy beats and the over the top voice over from the godfather of exotica.

7.title: That Summer
7.plot: The Vinyl Geek checks out a great soundtrack to a film you've never seen. If you're a fan of early punk, you won't want to miss this episode.

8.title: Mickey Katz: Mish Mosh
8.plot: Join the Vinyl Geek as he uncovers the origins of Oscar gold and dirty dancing with Mickey Katz.

9.title: Nilsson: The Point!
9.plot: The Vinyl Geek brings you one of his favorite childhood albums with Nilsson's The Point! Discover the story of Oblio and travels through the land of point.

10.title: Music for Hi-Fi Bugs: Pete Rugolo
10.plot: The Vinyl Geek reaches back into television history to bring you Pete Rugolo's "Music for Hi-Fi Bugs", a mid-century jazz gem.

11.title: Dino, Desi & Billy: I'm A Fool
11.plot: What do you do when you're the son of a Hollywood legend? Start a band of course. Join the Vinyl Geek as he discovers what it takes to be teen idols in the 1960's with Dino, Desi & Billy.

12.title: Conan the Barbarian
12.plot: This week he sets the tone for an epic month with the soundtrack to Conan The Barbarian.

13.title: Stand by Me
13.plot: The Vinyl Geek takes a trip down memory lane with "Stand By Me" soundtrack during May Movie Month on Vinyl Rewind.

14.title: The Hobbit
14.plot: This week, the Vinyl Geek travels to Middle Earth in search of soundtrack goodness.

15.title: The Black Hole
15.plot: May Movie Month continues on Vinyl Rewind with Disney's "The Black Hole" from 1979. Let the Vinyl Geek guide you through this John Barry sci/fi epic soundtrack with a little help from a new friend.

16.title: Vinyl Rewind's Memorial Day Special
16.plot: The Vinyl Geek shares some family history with a 67 year old acetate from World War Two on Vinyl Rewind's Memorial Day special.

17.title: Vinyl Rewind Updates
17.plot: The Vinyl Geek brings you some updates on the show.

18.title: Dare to Be Stupid
18.plot: This week, the Vinyl Geek brings you the most important record of his life: Weird Al's "Dare To Be Stupid" from 1985.

19.title: Moonglow by Artie Shaw
19.plot: Be on the lookout for some brand new show elements and the Vinyl Geeks reaches back to the swing era to bring you this classic compilation, "Moonglow" by Artie Shaw and his Orchestra.

20.title: The Specials
20.plot: This week, the Vinyl Geek revisits his misspent youth as a rudeboy growing up in Santa Cruz with The Specials' self-titled debut LP.

21.title: The Buggles
21.plot: This month MTV turns 30 and the Vinyl Geek is celebrating with The Buggles' The Age of Plastic from 1979.

22.title: Julie London
22.plot: The Vinyl Geek swoons over Julie London's "Julie Is Her Name" from 1955.

23.title: Vinyl Rewind's Tribute to Jani Lane
23.plot: The Vinyl Geek re-evaluates his opinion on the glam metal scene as he pays tribute to the late Jani Lane, the lead singer of Warrant.

24.title: Nirvana's Nevermind 20th Anniversary Special
24.plot: The Vinyl Geek celebrates the 20th Anniversary of Nirvana's groundbreaking album Nevermind.

25.title: Dance, Be Happy
25.plot: This week, the Vinyl Geek explores the 1957 Columbia records' compilation "Dance, Be Happy" and if decides if the record will really make you dance and be happy.

26.title: Kiss Me Deadly by GenX
26.plot: This week, the Vinyl Geek investigates Billy Idol's roots with Kiss Me Deadly? by GenX from 1981, then jumps 30 years to the present day with the film Drive.

27.title: Legend OST
27.plot: The Vinyl has a Tangerine Dream and travels to the magical, musical world of Ridley Scott's Legend from 1985 on MCA records.

28.title: Vinyl Rewind's Tribute to Freddie Mercury
28.plot: The 24th of this month marks the 20th anniversary of Freddie Mercury's death and this week, the Vinyl Geek pays tribute the late singer by reviewing Queen's "A Night at the Opera" from 1975.

29.title: God Bless Tiny Tim
29.plot: This week the Vinyl Geek tip-toe's to the bizarre and wacky sounds of the late, great Tiny Tim.

30.title: Season Update
30.plot: This week the Vinyl Geek shares some exciting news.

1.title: Sticky Fingers
1.plot: The Vinyl Geek dig's up an album with one of the most of the most iconic covers of all time: Sticky Fingers by the Rolling Stones from 1971. Get ready to learn some little known facts about this classic album from an unexpected source.

2.title: Vanilla Fudge
2.plot: This week, the Vinyl Geek learns you can't judge an album by its cover as he takes a psychedelic trip with the self-titled debut of Vanilla Fudge.

3.title: Interview with the Chop Tops
3.plot: The Chop Tops stop by the Vinyl Geek pad to talk about their recent exploits on the road and their first vinyl release, Deadly Love from 2010.

4.title: Esquivel! Other Worlds, Other Sounds
4.plot: The Vinyl Geek reviews the definitive album for your space aged, bachelor pad; Other Worlds, Other Sounds by Esquivel and his Orchestra from 1958 on RCA Records. Auntie Vinyl drops by the vinyl pad, uninvited and we welcome Miz Mel.

5.title: Record Store Day 2012
5.plot: The Vinyl Geek discovers the magic of Record Store Day 2012 with the help of an uninvited guest.

6.title: Gary Puckett and the Union Gap
6.plot: The Vinyl Geek stumbles upon a by-product of the "in sound" of the 1960s with Incredible by Gary Puckett and the Union Gap. Does it still hold up today?

7.title: The Lumineers
7.plot: The Vinyl Geek brings you his pick for the best debut album of 2012 with The Lumineers' self-titled LP. Join us as we listen to the beauty of this album with the help of our special guest, film director Ben Fee.

8.title: Confess by Twin Shadow
8.plot: The Vinyl Geek brings you an album from 2012 drenched in 80s New Wave: Confess by Twin Shadow on 4AD records. Is there more going on than just being "retro" - you decide.

9.title: The Top Ten Songs You Never Knew Were Covers
9.plot: This week the Vinyl Geek and Professor Watson count down the top ten songs you never knew were covers; the results may surprise you.

10.title: Big Al's Record Barn
10.plot: This week the Vinyl Geek makes a special trip to the mecca of all Bay Area record stores, Big Al's Record Barn. Join The Geek as we get to know Big Al, his store and why you should plan your own trip before it's too late.

1.title: The Dark Side of the Moon 40th Anniversary
1.plot: Come with the Vinyl Geek as he takes a very special trip to The Dark Side of the Moon; What starts as a simple 40th anniversary tribute of Pink Floyd's most popular album, may have the Geek in over his head.

2.title: The Beatles: 50th Anniversary
2.plot: This week the Vinyl Geek celebrates the 50th anniversary of The Beatles' first album, Please, Please me.

3.title: Time Out by the Dave Brubeck Quartet
3.plot: This week the Vinyl Geek brings you one of the greatest jazz albums, Time Out by The Dave Brubeck Quartet from 1959. Why not take five, mix your favorite cocktail and enjoy this classic record.

4.title: The Wildest by Louis Prima
4.plot: Vinyl Geek brings you Louis Prima's definitive album, The Wildest. Forget the Rack Pack, Louis is where it's at.

5.title: The Top Ten Songs About Star Wars
5.plot: Come celebrate the 30th Anniversary of Star Wars, Return of the Jedi with Vinyl Geek and Professor Watson as they count down the top ten original songs about Star Wars. No covers or parodies here, just iPod ready tracks for you to enjoy.

6.title: The Freewheelin' Bob Dylan: 50th Anniversary
6.plot: May 27 marks the 50th anniversary of Bob Dylan's break-through 2nd album, The Freewheelin' Bob Dylan. Join the Vinyl Geek as he uncovers little known facts about the album and gets a visit by someone unexpected.

7.title: MC Lars: Greatest Hits
7.plot: This week a very special guest pops by the Vinyl Pad as the Vinyl Geek takes a closer look at The Greatest Hits of MC Lars, a new double LP compilation, chronically the past 10 years of the artist's career.

8.title: Top Ten Live vs. Studio Recordings
8.plot: This week the Vinyl Geek and Professor Watson are counting down the top ten live versions of songs that are more popular than their studio counterparts.

9.title: Chico Buarque - Construção with Sister Rogers
9.plot: This week the Vinyl Geek invites the LA local band, Sister Rogers, over to the Vinyl Pad to talk about Brazilian singer/ songwriter Chico Buarque's 1971 album Construção.

10.title: The Smashing Pumpkins - Siamese Dream 20th Anniversary
10.plot: This week the Vinyl Geek remembers the seminal second album by The Smashing Pumpkins, as Siamese Dream turns 20 this month.

11.title: The New York Dolls: Too Much Too Soon
11.plot: This week the Vinyl Geek delves into one of the most underrated bands of all time with The New York Dolls second album Too Much, Too Soon from 1974.

12.title: The Jam: In the City
12.plot: It's a Mod Mod World on Vinyl Rewind as the Vinyl Geek brings you the greatest UK band you've probably never heard. It's The Jam with their self-titled, debut album.

13.title: Metallica's and Justice for All 25th Anniversary
13.plot: This week the Vinyl Geek discovers just what makes Metallica so great as he celebrates the 25th anniversary of And Justice For All.

14.title: David Bowie's First Official Live Album: David Live
14.plot: This week the Vinyl Geek checks out David Bowie's first official live album, David Live, with the help from Alexandra & Zachary from Alexandra & The Starlight Band. We also take a peak at their vinyl releases.

15.title: Electric Light Orchestra - Time
15.plot: On this week's episode, Manimal Vinyl recording artist, Baron Von Luxxury stops by the Vinyl Pad, as he and the Vinyl Geek travel to the future with Electric Light Orchestra's 1981 concept album, "Time".

16.title: Tears for Fears: The Hurting
16.plot: On this week's episode, Tommy Boy recording artist Jamar Rogers stops by the Vinyl Pad to discuss the debut album by Tears for Fears, "The Hurting" from 1983 on Mercury Records.

17.title: The Zombies: Odessey and Oracle
17.plot: Before War World Z and The Walking Dead there were these Zombies. San Diego based band Mrs. Magician stops by the Vinyl Pad to discus the The Zombies' magnum opus, "Odessey And Oracle" from 1968.

1.title: Herb Alpert - Whipped Cream & Other Delights
1.plot: This week The Vinyl Geek whips up a tasty review for Herb Alpert's cult-classic, cheesecake album, Whipped Cream & Other Delights. What The Geek discovers may surprise you.

2.title: Top Eight Celebrity Albums of the 1980s
2.plot: This week The Vinyl Geek & Auntie Vinyl count down the Top Eight Celebrity Albums of the 1980s. Who made the number one spot? Watch and find out.

3.title: The Geek's Top 10 Desert Island Discs
3.plot: The Vinyl Geek counts down his Top 10 Desert Island Discs. Which albums made the cut? Watch and find out.

4.title: The Beatles Rubber Soul - UK vs. USA
4.plot: The Beatles are notorious for having different versions of the same album released on either side of the Atlantic so we thought it'd be fun to figure which version The Vinyl Geek likes better.

5.title: You're a Good Man Charlie Brown OST
5.plot: This week The Vinyl Geek gets extra nostalgic while fulfilling a special request by reviewing the original cast soundtrack of the musical, You're A Good Man Charlie Brown.

6.title: Weezer "Blue" Vinyl Review
6.plot: This week, The Vinyl Geek takes a look back at Weezer's iconic "Blue Album. Not only is this one of the most influential albums of the last 20 years, it's one of the most important records in the Geek's life. Watch and find out why.

7.title: Dust & Grooves Book Review & Creator Interview
7.plot: This week, The Vinyl Geek sits down with Eilon Paz and Sheila Burgel of Dust and Grooves to talk about the brand new photo book dedicated to vinyl collectors titled Dust and Grooves: Adventures in Record Collecting.

8.title: King Crimson - In the Court of the Crimson King
8.plot: This week, The Vinyl Geek showcases one of the most influential prog-rock albums of all time, King Crimson's In The Court of the Crimson King from 1969 on Atlantic Records.

9.title: Lou Reed - Transformer
9.plot: By special request, The Vinyl Geek reviews Lou Reed's classic, 1972 album Transformer on RCA Records.

10.title: The Beatles - A Hard Day's Night - UK Vs. USA
10.plot: This week The Vinyl Geek is back with another verses episode, this time around he takes a look at A Hard Day's Night Soundtrack, UK vs. USA. Which one is better? Watch and find out.

11.title: Mandatory Fun
11.plot: Director Tim Thompson stops by the Vinyl Pad to discuss working with Al, making the music video for "Lame Claim To Fame", and Weird Al's latest, Mandatory Fun on RCA from 2014.

12.title: Vinyl Rewind's 2014 Interactive Halloween Special
12.plot: Will the Geek safely navigate through a witch house and restore order to Arkham? Only one way to find out.

13.title: The Runaways Vinyl Review with Guest, Tom Carroll
13.plot: Tom Carroll from the fantastic YouTube channel, Tom Explores LA, stops by the Vinyl Pad to talk about the debut album by The Runaways, from 1976 on Mercury Records.

14.title: Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band Vinyl Review
14.plot: This week the Vinyl Geek reviews the Beatles' 1967 classic album, Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band on Capitol/ Parlophone Records. Is this the greatest album of all time? Watch and find out.

15.title: Music for Dining - The Melachrino Strings Vinyl Overview
15.plot: The Vinyl Geek briefly goes over the various vinyl releases of George Melachrino's classic mood music album Music for Dining from 1954 on RCA Records. Oh yeah, happy Thanksgiving.

1.title: The Beach Boys - Pet Sounds Vinyl Review
1.plot: This week The Vinyl Geek explores the defining album by the seminal 60s group, The Beach Boys, Pet Sounds from 1966 on Capitol Records.

8.title: Prince - Sign "O" the Times Vinyl Album Review
8.plot: This week The Vinyl Geek pays tribute to Prince by reviewing one of his best and highly underrated album, Sign "O" The Times from 1987 on Warner Bros Records.
